brewery.brewery_description:
In August 1903 the Tsingtao Brewery was founded by adventure driven German and British settlers in Qingdao, China.
At present, Tsingtao Beer is exported to more than 100 countries and regions in the world such as the United States, Canada, Britain, France, Germany, Italy, Australia, South Korea, Japan, Denmark, Russia, etc., and is the fifth largest beer producer in the world.

items.checkin_comment: Very very sweet, slight roast flavour, translucent and without much punch. However, the qingdao brewery gave me a liter of it for less than £3.

beer.beer_description: Pours black color, clear dark brown in closer look, big brownish head. Burnt malt on the nose. Aroma is licorice, dark malts, malzbier, dark bread, toasted malts, cocoa and coffee. Taste is somewhat sweetish, chocolateish, with a bitter dar chocolate finish. Carbonation is sustained, body is medium, finish is dusty, s bit sticky still quite dry, alcoholic. Quite good unexpectedly, tasty.

items.checkin_comment: The guy took the bottle before I got the photo, but I’ve been drinking it at least 30 years so it’s all good.

beer.beer_description:
Tsingtao Beer has a pleasant aroma and a well-balanced taste. It has high-malty flavor and well-hopped character. Tsingtao is produced with spring water from Laoshan, a mountain area famous throughout China for the purity of its water. The domestically-grown hops used to brew Tsingtao are of such high quality that they are also exported to European breweries. Tsingtao also uses the finest yeast and barley imported from Australia and Canada in its brewing process. 

Made partly with rice as an adjunct.

Tsingtao Pure Draft is a smooth, crisp and light-tasting draft beer. It is brewed with domestically-grown hops, select barley, all-natural yeast and pure spring water from China’s Laoshan Mountains. Tsingtao Pure Draft is brewed with an exclusive low temperature filtration process preserving the beer’s true flavor to create an incredibly refreshing beer-drinking experience. It is the perfect accompaniment to Pan-Asian cuisine and light appetizers.
Not to be confused with tsingtao wheat beer, this one has less ABV
